Part 1: Data

The Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) is a collaborative project amongst all the states in the United States and participating US territories and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. BRFSS is an ongoing surveillance system designed to measure behavioral risk factors for the non-institutionalized adult population (18 years of age and older) residing in the US. Its objective is to collect uniform, state-specific data on preventive health practices and risk behaviors that are linked to chronic diseases, injuries, and preventable infectious diseases that affect the adult population. 

The BRFSS is an observational study and not an experimental one with random assignment - any relationship amongst variables will only indicate association and not causation.

The BRFSS collects data of the adult population residing in the U.S. Data is collected via landline telephone and cellular telephone surveys on a randomly selected adult in a household and adult participating uses a cellular device and resides in private residence or college housing. Data is also collected across 56 participating states participating in the BRFSS. According to this, adequate random sample is collected to ensure that the given data is generalizable to the larger U.S. population. However, even though this methodology attempts to be able to accurately portray and be generalized to the larger population, it also provides some bias towards particular individuals being selected for the survey.

Several biases include; - Only people with access to landline telephone and cellular telephone are surveyed - Not all selected adults respond to telephone surveys - Not all selected adults will be knowledgeable of the answers to the survey questions and thus may provide inaccurate responses

Part 2: Research questions

Research quesion 1:

  1. Is an individual’s education level and income level linked? Would their gender play a role in this linkage?

This question poses real life dilemmas it is commonly known that higher advanced degrees usually indicate different levels of income. Also, the variable of gender could also play a role in one’s education level and income level due to social norms, pay equity and discrimination.

Variables involved were: - educa: Education Level - income2: Income Level - sex: Reported Gender

Research quesion 2:

  1. Is a respondents amount of time slept related to their difficulty remembering and concentrating? Would being a veteran also have an effect?

Post traumatic stress disorder is apparent within the veteran population. Being a veteran could be of relation with amount of sleep time had. Typical symptoms of PTSD is associated with a sleep disorder.

Variables involved were: - Sleptim1: How Much Time Do You Sleep - Veteran3: Are You A Veteran

Research quesion 3:

  1. Does how often we undergo physical activity show any association with our general health? Also, would being overweight/obese also influence general health?

Physical activity is often linked with ones general health as well as whether one is obese/overweight. Plotting the different physical activity level of different groups with their respective general health should amount to adequate difference between the groups general health. We can also explore the obese vs non-obese groups of people as another variable to the plot.

Variables involved were: - Genhlth: General Health - _pacat1: Physical Activity Categories - _rfbmi5: Overweight Or Obese Calculated Variable

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Next, I decided to form a graphical visualization of the three variables using the geom_jitter function within the ggplot library. I placed the education level as the X axis and the reported incomes on the Y axis. We can then see the visualization and note the difference in the amount of jitter points within each section of the geom according to an individuals education level and reported income. Note how as we progress down the X axis (left to right) – more jitter points are located toward the higher reported income.

plot1 <- ggplot(rsq1, aes(x = educa, y = income2))+ geom_jitter(size = 1/80, alpha = 1/20) + scale_x_discrete(labels = c('A','B','C','D','E','F'))
plot1

#Note. A - Never attended school or only kindergarten
#B - Grades 1 through 8 (elementary)
#C - Grades 9 through 11 (Some high school)
#D - Grades 12 or GED (High school graduate)
#E - College 1 year to 3 years (Some college or technical school)
#F - College 4 years or more (College graduate)

Next, I added the variable of sex using the facet_grid function. This splits the geom into two separate visualizations (male and female). We can find the association between education level and reported income – specifically, a higher education level indicates a higher reported income due to the larger amount of jitter points in the indicated regions on the plot.

plot1 <- plot1 + facet_grid(. ~ sex) + xlab("Education Level") + ylab("Reported Income")
plot1

Using geom_violin to visualise the data – I plotted rsq2 with veteran status on the x axis and time slept on the y axis. In addition, I used the ylim parameter of 3,11 to remove the abnormal values from the data set (e.g. 450 hour’s time slept of one respondent)

plot2 <- ggplot(rsq2, aes(x = veteran3, y = sleptim1)) +
  geom_violin() +
  xlab("Are you a veteran?") +
  ylab ("Time Slept (hours)") +
  ylim(c(3,11))
plot2
## Warning: Removed 6671 rows containing non-finite values (stat_ydensity).

The plot indicates a larger amount of non-veterans having a normal sleep time as there is a wider band within the regions of 6-9 hours as opposed to the veterans which have a narrower band located within the regions of 6-9 hours. This indicates that there is a larger amount of non-veterans with normal sleeping hours.

Research quesion 3:

Research Question 3: Does how often we undergo physical activity show any association with our general health? Also, would being overweight/obese also influence general health?

As all of the variables are categorical data, I decided to use the geom_bar function for my data visualization method and use (position=”fill”) to scale the proportions of general health to 1 for a better representation. Note that I needed to rotate the x labels so that we are able to read the x labels.

plot3 <- ggplot(rsq3, aes(x = X_pacat1, fill = genhlth)) +
  geom_bar(position='fill') +
  xlab("Physical Activity Categories") +
  ylab("Ratio") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name="General Health") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))
plot3

Lastly I added the third variable of X_rfbmi5 which is a categorical variable that states whether the respondent was obese or not. This variable had data in a “yes” or “no” factor format, thus I changed it to “Not Obese (<25 bmi)” and “Obese (>25 bmi)” for a clearer visualization

summary(rsq3$X_rfbmi5)
##     No    Yes 
## 136683 258155
levels(rsq3$X_rfbmi5) <- c("Not Obese (<25 bmi)","Obese (>25 bmi)")
plot3 <- plot3 +
  facet_grid(.~rsq3$X_rfbmi5)
  plot3

The above visualization indicates an association between the physical activity category that the respondent is in and their respective general health. The plot indicates that the group of people who are more active have a greater ratio of better general health. This means that being more physically active indicates better general health as well as vice versa. After the addition of the third variable using the fact_grid function – we find that there is also an association between whether the respondent was obese or not and their general health. The group who aren’t obese have a higher ratio of better general health across all physical activity categories.
